ng pull of something even worse seeking to devour him. This sheer encounter with malevolence shatters Dan's mind. He wakes in a coma, speaking in the confused tongues that fell over humanity after the Tower of Babel. Although he spoke the same language he had always spoken, no one could understand him. Upon his recovery, he sheds his last \"earthly treasure,\" his wineskin, symbolizing his complete liberation from even the body’s essential needs. He now carries only two smooth stones. The stones are symbolic of Hope and Faith, the only thing Dan finds worthy of carrying with him and the only thing that he believes can be taken with him through death. As he nears the Sea of Galilee, he encounters the Sea Peoples. Having no material possessions but a couple of \"worthless\" stones, they take what he values most: his right eye. Th",
